01:21:56.770 --> 01:21:58.490
That means look, right?"

01:21:58.490 --> 01:22:01.270 position:56%
I smiled, and said, "Yeah, it does."

01:22:01.270 --> 01:22:03.160
Leia, in her first
moments in Finland,

01:22:03.160 --> 01:22:05.430
was channelling what she knew
of the language of the country

01:22:05.430 --> 01:22:07.520
that her family had
left so long ago,

01:22:07.520 --> 01:22:10.500
but which hadn't entirely
left them yet.

01:22:10.500 --> 01:22:13.350 position:56%
It shouldn't be incredibly
surprising that Leia, a young woman,

01:22:13.350 --> 01:22:15.810
would be able to recall words
and their meaning in a language

01:22:15.810 --> 01:22:17.420
in which she was not fluent.

01:22:17.420 --> 01:22:18.800
Her home community
in Houghton County,

01:22:18.800 --> 01:22:20.790
Michigan boasts the
largest concentration

01:22:20.790 --> 01:22:24.710
of ethnic Finns outside of Finland,
and over the past 100 years,

01:22:24.710 --> 01:22:27.320 position:56%
Finnish language and culture have
continued to have an important place

01:22:27.320 --> 01:22:29.580
in the community's
private and public life.

01:22:29.580 --> 01:22:34.330
According to the 2013 U.S. Census
American Community Survey estimate,

01:22:34.330 --> 01:22:37.910
just under 32% of Houghton County
residents indicated Finnish

01:22:37.910 --> 01:22:41.520
as being either their primary
or secondary ethnic ancestry.

01:22:41.520 --> 01:22:44.090
This means that, in this
county, they are the largest --

01:22:44.090 --> 01:22:45.390
they are the ethnic majority.

01:22:45.390 --> 01:22:48.790
As can be seen in this map that we
can't see, but I can show you later

01:22:48.790 --> 01:22:51.940
if you're interested, Finnish
ancestry is a rather common trait

01:22:51.940 --> 01:22:55.750 position:56%
across the Lake Superior region,
which includes Minnesota, Wisconsin,

01:22:55.750 --> 01:22:58.310
upper Michigan, and areas
around Ontario, too.

01:22:58.310 --> 01:23:01.990 position:56%
And so we affectionately know of
this region as being the Sauna Belt.

01:23:01.990 --> 01:23:03.870
And if you ever need a
sauna, just drive around.

01:23:03.870 --> 01:23:05.170
You'll see one.

01:23:05.170 --> 01:23:06.470
You can ask.

01:23:06.470 --> 01:23:08.590
In everyday terms, this means that
Finnish culture is a visible part

01:23:08.590 --> 01:23:11.310
of the community for those
who are Finnish or not.

01:23:11.310 --> 01:23:15.490
Finns, though originally heavily
stigmatized as being undesirable,

01:23:15.490 --> 01:23:18.930
second-wave, eastern European
immigrants in the late 1800s,

01:23:18.930 --> 01:23:22.620
have gradually come to a place
of semi-esteem in the region,

01:23:22.620 --> 01:23:26.130
and have asserted pride in their
culture in a number of ways.

01:23:26.130 --> 01:23:28.920
In Houghton County and places
like it, towns with Finnish names

01:23:28.920 --> 01:23:31.260
like Doyvila [assumed
spelling], Isanti, Tapiola

01:23:31.260 --> 01:23:33.760
and Oulu dot the map,
though the pronunciation

01:23:33.760 --> 01:23:36.880
of these words may differ from
how we would hear them in Finland.

01:23:36.880 --> 01:23:38.180
Businesses have Finnish names,

01:23:38.180 --> 01:23:40.090
either because of the
proprietor's surname,

01:23:40.090 --> 01:23:42.900
or because of a conscious
decision to use a Finnish name.

01:23:42.900 --> 01:23:45.990
Restaurants may offer Finnish baked
goods, and churches originating

01:23:45.990 --> 01:23:47.640
from the Finnish State
Lutheran Church

01:23:47.640 --> 01:23:51.890
or the Northern Nordic Laestadian
Lutheran Movement are found

01:23:51.890 --> 01:23:54.050
in abundance in this region.

01:23:54.050 --> 01:23:56.760
And there are people who speak
this language in varying degrees

01:23:56.760 --> 01:24:00.420
from native and near-native fluency
to the use of a sprinkling of terms

01:24:00.420 --> 01:24:02.250
that maintained for
a variety of reasons.

01:24:02.250 --> 01:24:04.940
And I will describe this variable
situation for you in this paper.

01:24:04.940 --> 01:24:09.020
Finns began to come to the upper
midwest starting in the 1860s,

01:24:09.020 --> 01:24:11.150
with work opportunities
in mining as a result

01:24:11.150 --> 01:24:14.000
of the Civil War production
and worker shortages.

01:24:14.000 --> 01:24:16.440
It is merely a coincidence that
these migrants should have come

01:24:16.440 --> 01:24:19.120
to a place that is geographically
so similar to Finland.

01:24:19.120 --> 01:24:21.940
A common idea among
Finnish-Americans and those

01:24:21.940 --> 01:24:26.160
that learn about them is that
this similarity drew the Finns,

01:24:26.160 --> 01:24:27.460
but this is not based in truth.

01:24:27.460 --> 01:24:29.580
It's perhaps rather a
good deal of serendipity,

01:24:29.580 --> 01:24:31.770
especially when they started
farming, and they knew exactly how

01:24:31.770 --> 01:24:33.220
to farm in a rocky, frozen place

01:24:33.220 --> 01:24:35.710
that has a super short
growing season.

01:24:35.710 --> 01:24:38.310
When they came, they knew no
English, and they were relegated

01:24:38.310 --> 01:24:41.550 position:56%
to the hard labor jobs that required
little talking beyond gestures,

01:24:41.550 --> 01:24:44.640
shouts indicating danger, and
basic mining vocabulary learned

01:24:44.640 --> 01:24:46.250
on the job.

01:24:46.250 --> 01:24:49.280
Under these circumstances, it was
rather common for Finnish-Americans

01:24:49.280 --> 01:24:51.560
to create a Finnish
language community in order

01:24:51.560 --> 01:24:54.130
to meet their basic needs
in their new setting.

01:24:54.130 --> 01:24:57.200
With a higher literacy rate than
similar recently-arrived groups,

01:24:57.200 --> 01:24:59.570
Finns had the means to create
their own infrastructure,

01:24:59.570 --> 01:25:02.840
and over the next half-century,
Finnish language businesses,

01:25:02.840 --> 01:25:06.590
newspapers, temperance
societies, churches, workers' halls

01:25:06.590 --> 01:25:08.400
and other concerns
became rather common

01:25:08.400 --> 01:25:09.970
in the areas in which they settled.

01:25:09.970 --> 01:25:13.720
As many Finns still arrived to
the towns that offered jobs,

01:25:13.720 --> 01:25:15.710
others were able to retreat
into the countryside,

01:25:15.710 --> 01:25:18.300
and to create farming
communities based on homesteads

01:25:18.300 --> 01:25:21.470
and stump farms created on
the leavings of lumberjacks.

01:25:21.470 --> 01:25:23.560
Under these conditions,
and due to the fact

01:25:23.560 --> 01:25:26.390
that Finnish was incomprehensible
to any other linguistic community

01:25:26.390 --> 01:25:29.550 position:56%
in the reason, Finnish was able to
live on in some form for much longer

01:25:29.550 --> 01:25:32.230
than many of the other immigrant
languages in the region.

01:25:32.230 --> 01:25:36.690
As Finns incorporated further
into the local community,

01:25:36.690 --> 01:25:40.420 position:56%
a unique transitional dialect known
as Finglish or Fingliskad developed,

01:25:40.420 --> 01:25:42.330
merging Finnish and
sometimes Swedish words

01:25:42.330 --> 01:25:44.780
with Finnish word order, phonetics
and grammatical roles, and --

01:25:44.780 --> 01:25:46.080
actually, Dan probably --

01:25:46.080 --> 01:25:47.440
Dan has actually taught
me a lot about Finglish.

01:25:47.440 --> 01:25:50.110
I really appreciate his early
comments in some of my research

01:25:50.110 --> 01:25:51.410
when it first started out.

01:25:51.410 --> 01:25:54.260
So he probably has great
things to say about it.

01:25:54.260 --> 01:25:56.100
So this language, to say the least,

01:25:56.100 --> 01:25:57.950
is extremely creative
and fun to use.

01:25:57.950 --> 01:25:59.430
And an example of its creativity,

01:25:59.430 --> 01:26:01.330
which I don't have the
visual graphic for,

01:26:01.330 --> 01:26:02.690
would be the sentence
[foreign language].

01:26:02.690 --> 01:26:08.070
Is there anybody here who
knows what that means?

01:26:08.070 --> 01:26:09.720
Yes -- yeah.

01:26:09.720 --> 01:26:12.010
Because we were pushed into
that [foreign language], right?

01:26:12.010 --> 01:26:14.780
Okay, so -- but -- so
this is actually --

01:26:14.780 --> 01:26:20.530
