01:29:04.580 --> 01:29:07.400
Okay. So the pressures of
Americanization are compounded

01:29:07.400 --> 01:29:10.360
by these local inter-ethnic
problems, including suspiciousness

01:29:10.360 --> 01:29:13.140
against Finnish leftist
political and labor organizations

01:29:13.140 --> 01:29:15.670
from the 1910s to the 1950s.

01:29:15.670 --> 01:29:18.200
In the upper midwest, this
resulted from several divisive

01:29:18.200 --> 01:29:20.820
and deadly labor strikes,
resultant blacklisting

01:29:20.820 --> 01:29:23.920
and general social deprecation
of Finns, the residual effects

01:29:23.920 --> 01:29:27.400
which live on today in areas
such as the copper country.

01:29:27.400 --> 01:29:30.640
To speak Finnish in public areas
marked you as disloyal and radical

01:29:30.640 --> 01:29:33.530
at worst, and a provincial
bumpkin at best.

01:29:33.530 --> 01:29:36.540
It -- this didn't, however,
stop Finnish-Americans

01:29:36.540 --> 01:29:39.160
from using their language in
several venues that were safe to --

01:29:39.160 --> 01:29:42.370
safe to use it in, including
the church and the home.

01:29:42.370 --> 01:29:46.040
From 1962 until 2014, the
Evangelical Lutheran Church

01:29:46.040 --> 01:29:49.450
of America maintained a special
Suomi conference of the church

01:29:49.450 --> 01:29:51.960
to reflect the needs of
Finnish ethnic parishioners.

01:29:51.960 --> 01:29:54.330
And people to this day
still sing Christmas carols,

01:29:54.330 --> 01:29:57.730 position:56%
make Finnish foods, take saunas,
and use a variety of obscure Finnish

01:29:57.730 --> 01:30:00.280
and Finglish words to
describe everyday things.

01:30:00.280 --> 01:30:02.620
This is where Finnish starts to
come in as a heritage language.

01:30:02.620 --> 01:30:05.470
A heritage language, though often
defined in many multiple ways

01:30:05.470 --> 01:30:08.620
by linguists, is meant here
by me as being a language

01:30:08.620 --> 01:30:10.970
that a person recognizes
as having a relationship

01:30:10.970 --> 01:30:12.370
with that person's
own ethnic heritage,

01:30:12.370 --> 01:30:14.180 position:56%
whether they speak any of it or not.

01:30:14.180 --> 01:30:16.390
So it has a significance to
them as a part of their own kind

01:30:16.390 --> 01:30:18.070
of internal sense of culture.

01:30:18.070 --> 01:30:23.110
In the 1960s and 1970s,
Finnish-Americans took part

01:30:23.110 --> 01:30:24.800
in a resurgence of ethnic identity

01:30:24.800 --> 01:30:26.990
that was also taking place among
many other white Americans,

01:30:26.990 --> 01:30:29.000
and this is also after
the Civil Rights Movement.

01:30:29.000 --> 01:30:30.700
So this was a whole
period in American life

01:30:30.700 --> 01:30:33.840 position:56%
when people were asserting
different identities, and, you know,

01:30:33.840 --> 01:30:37.820
a lot of great, wonderful
things came out of that.

01:30:37.820 --> 01:30:40.230 position:56%
It was also an opportunity for these
previously marginalized groups,

01:30:40.230 --> 01:30:42.520
including Finnish-Americans
in the upper midwest,

01:30:42.520 --> 01:30:43.820
to look at their heritage
in a new light.

01:30:43.820 --> 01:30:45.790
And this happened at
about the same time

01:30:45.790 --> 01:30:47.680
that longstanding Finnish
community groups,

01:30:47.680 --> 01:30:50.750
including temperance societies,
Finnish-language churches,

01:30:50.750 --> 01:30:53.180
and consumer cooperatives,
were having their last splash

01:30:53.180 --> 01:30:55.030
with the Finnish language,
and were moving

01:30:55.030 --> 01:30:56.760
to primarily English-language
groups,

01:30:56.760 --> 01:30:58.980
if not disbanding altogether.

01:30:58.980 --> 01:31:01.650 position:56%
At this time, the loss of the
language became a source of distress

01:31:01.650 --> 01:31:03.160
within the community,
and they started throwing

01:31:03.160 --> 01:31:05.730
out ropes to rescue the language.

01:31:05.730 --> 01:31:08.040
The Salolampi Finnish Language
Camp was one of the first,

01:31:08.040 --> 01:31:10.260
most concrete examples
of an institution

01:31:10.260 --> 01:31:12.690
that was created specifically to
teach Finnish language to youth

01:31:12.690 --> 01:31:14.730
in the ethnic group, and also
outside the ethnic group.

01:31:14.730 --> 01:31:17.420
A lot of people from all walks
of life have gone to Salolampi.

01:31:17.420 --> 01:31:21.040
It's a camp that's run by Concordia
University in Morehead, Minnesota,

01:31:21.040 --> 01:31:23.620
and it provides a total immersive
language learning environment

01:31:23.620 --> 01:31:25.400
in which English is not used.

01:31:25.400 --> 01:31:27.010
For many Finnish-American youth,

01:31:27.010 --> 01:31:30.390
this camp has become an important
experience in their childhood.

01:31:30.390 --> 01:31:33.010
Finnish language has also been
offered, at least since the 1970s,

01:31:33.010 --> 01:31:34.920
at the University of
Minnesota Twin Cities.

01:31:34.920 --> 01:31:36.220
I think -- was Boutier
[assumed spelling] maybe the one

01:31:36.220 --> 01:31:37.520
who started that?

01:31:37.520 --> 01:31:38.820
&gt;&gt; '60s.

01:31:38.820 --> 01:31:40.120
&gt;&gt; Hillary Virtanen: '60s.

01:31:40.120 --> 01:31:41.420
Oh, okay. Good.

01:31:41.420 --> 01:31:42.720
&gt;&gt; Even before that.

01:31:42.720 --> 01:31:44.020
&gt;&gt; Hillary Virtanen:
Even before that.

01:31:44.020 --> 01:31:45.320
But, yeah, it kind of really
gets -- gets in there.

01:31:45.320 --> 01:31:46.620
And it's been taught off and
on at Finlandia University,

01:31:46.620 --> 01:31:47.920
which was known as Suomi
College until 2000,

01:31:47.920 --> 01:31:49.300
as well as the University
of Wisconsin, Madison.

01:31:49.300 --> 01:31:51.160
So this means that
ethnic Finns that live

01:31:51.160 --> 01:31:54.230
in the region have a wide variety
of study options for, you know,

01:31:54.230 --> 01:31:56.760
local and regional universities.

01:31:56.760 --> 01:31:59.490 position:56%
Community language classes have
also been offered in varying degrees

01:31:59.490 --> 01:32:02.350
in small institutions across
the midwest that have a stake

01:32:02.350 --> 01:32:05.990 position:56%
in maintaining Finnish traditions
in the everyday, including language.

01:32:05.990 --> 01:32:08.540
At the Finnish-American Heritage
Center in Hancock, Michigan,

01:32:08.540 --> 01:32:10.810
for instance, community Finnish
classes have been offered

01:32:10.810 --> 01:32:12.840
since the 1990s.

01:32:12.840 --> 01:32:15.650
In 2004, I undertook a
survey of students currently

01:32:15.650 --> 01:32:18.590
or previously enrolled in the
Finnish language classes offered

01:32:18.590 --> 01:32:19.890
in high schools in Houghton County,

01:32:19.890 --> 01:32:21.880
Michigan through a
distance learning program.

01:32:21.880 --> 01:32:24.010
These schools created the
distance learning program in order

01:32:24.010 --> 01:32:26.920
to increase course offerings in
the rural schools of the area.

01:32:26.920 --> 01:32:29.790
It was an opportunity to understand
both the cultural experiences

01:32:29.790 --> 01:32:32.630 position:56%
of the students who studied Finnish,
their attitudes toward the language,

01:32:32.630 --> 01:32:34.000
and their ideas for its future

01:32:34.000 --> 01:32:35.590
through their own interactions
with it.

01:32:35.590 --> 01:32:37.590
High school Finnish
is no longer offered

01:32:37.590 --> 01:32:39.170
in the Houghton County
schools, unfortunately.

01:32:39.170 --> 01:32:41.680
Those students do have
the opportunity to take it

01:32:41.680 --> 01:32:44.600
through community enrichment
classes at Finlandia University,

01:32:44.600 --> 01:32:47.380
or in dual-enrollment programs
through Finlandia University,

01:32:47.380 --> 01:32:49.650
but that's a little more
difficult, just scheduling-wise,

01:32:49.650 --> 01:32:51.620
and also because it's
a very rural area.

01:32:51.620 --> 01:32:53.740
So kids would have to drive
pretty far for, you know,

01:32:53.740 --> 01:32:55.900
an hour-long class
four times a week.

01:32:55.900 --> 01:32:58.570
High school foreign language
classes are generally designed

01:32:58.570 --> 01:33:00.330
to create a certain
level of fluency,

01:33:00.330 --> 01:33:02.660
and to provide a very minimal
amount of cultural instruction.

01:33:02.660 --> 01:33:05.790
So if you've ever taken Spanish,
or French, and any other language

01:33:05.790 --> 01:33:08.760
at a public school in the U.S., you
know the basic formula for this.

01:33:08.760 --> 01:33:11.240
In the heritage context, however,
there are added imperatives

01:33:11.240 --> 01:33:15.120
and interests, and value-added
curricula address these concerns.

01:33:15.120 --> 01:33:17.890
Students attended concerts of
Finnish folk music and participated

01:33:17.890 --> 01:33:19.980
in Finnish Independence
Day celebrations.

01:33:19.980 --> 01:33:22.160
They conducted family
history projects.

01:33:22.160 --> 01:33:24.990
One of these students is standing
before you today, holding a Ph.D.

01:33:24.990 --> 01:33:28.010 position:56%
in Scandinavian folklore, and taking
my own students to Finland each year

01:33:28.010 --> 01:33:30.110
for their own discoveries
and connections.

01:33:30.110 --> 01:33:33.070
So in my survey, I was connected
-- I was concerned with the level

01:33:33.070 --> 01:33:35.570
and types of exposures students
had to aspects of Finnish culture

01:33:35.570 --> 01:33:39.190
in America, including language,
food ways, traditional arts, music,

01:33:39.190 --> 01:33:40.970
and popular culture from Finland.

01:33:40.970 --> 01:33:43.510
These students' experiences differ
sharply from the experiences

01:33:43.510 --> 01:33:47.550
and motivations of non-ethnic
students, who I've also taught

01:33:47.550 --> 01:33:49.810
at the University of
Wisconsin and Finlandia.

01:33:49.810 --> 01:33:51.110
While Finnish popular culture

01:33:51.110 --> 01:33:54.380
and particularly heavy metal
music typically attract non-Finns,

01:33:54.380 --> 01:33:56.510
Finnish-American students will
often be completely unaware

01:33:56.510 --> 01:33:58.680
of Finnish pop culture,
and may know about,

01:33:58.680 --> 01:34:01.720
if not completely identify with,
the older Finnish-American culture

01:34:01.720 --> 01:34:04.570
of the 1940s and 1950s
that their grandparents

01:34:04.570 --> 01:34:06.740
and other elders have
presented as authentic.

01:34:06.740 --> 01:34:10.240
In the survey, nine of the 10
respondents explicitly cited their

01:34:10.240 --> 01:34:12.530
family heritage as being the
motivating factor for them

01:34:12.530 --> 01:34:14.330
to study Finnish, and the student

01:34:14.330 --> 01:34:16.860
who didn't specifically say
this actually provided answers

01:34:16.860 --> 01:34:20.120
that indicated that this was
also the case for him or her.

01:34:20.120 --> 01:34:22.700 position:56%
Students were interested in learning
about Finland's history and culture,

01:34:22.700 --> 01:34:25.810
and many either had visited
Finland or had hopes to do so.

01:34:25.810 --> 01:34:27.300
Their language exposure outside

01:34:27.300 --> 01:34:29.840
of class typically included
the family use of small sets

01:34:29.840 --> 01:34:33.830
of vocabulary -- for instance,
swear words or exclamations.

01:34:33.830 --> 01:34:37.320
A lot of us learned those as
our first words, me included.

01:34:37.320 --> 01:34:39.680
Through their language study,
they all increased their knowledge

01:34:39.680 --> 01:34:41.980
of Finland itself and
of Finnish America.

01:34:41.980 --> 01:34:44.360
As these were anonymous
surveys, I don't have the ability

01:34:44.360 --> 01:34:47.190
to track these respondents today,
but they provide important clues

01:34:47.190 --> 01:34:50.030
to youth attitudes toward
Finnish as a heritage language.

01:34:50.030 --> 01:34:52.840
For many of these, languages served
to possibly rekindle the language,

01:34:52.840 --> 01:34:55.020
as their parents typically
didn't speak Finnish,

01:34:55.020 --> 01:34:56.550
and many grandparents did.

01:34:56.550 --> 01:34:59.100
So a lot of students specifically
said, "I can talk to my grandpa,

01:34:59.100 --> 01:35:01.040
and my mom and dad don't
know what we're saying."

01:35:01.040 --> 01:35:03.850
So, I mean, I think grandpa's got
some juicy gossip or something.

01:35:03.850 --> 01:35:06.430
So these surveys reveal the fact

01:35:06.430 --> 01:35:09.050
that there are these positive
attitudes toward Finnish language

01:35:09.050 --> 01:35:11.130
that exist in Houghton County.

01:35:11.130 --> 01:35:13.850
Other, more observational,
data also supports this.

01:35:13.850 --> 01:35:16.360
Periodic birth announcements
in the local paper reveal that,

01:35:16.360 --> 01:35:19.290
over the past 15 years or
so, Finnish names are popular

01:35:19.290 --> 01:35:21.100
with parents naming
babies, and often,

01:35:21.100 --> 01:35:23.000
these names reflect a
Finnish-American past,

01:35:23.000 --> 01:35:25.110
as opposed to naming
trends in Finland today.

01:35:25.110 --> 01:35:30.180
So in 2013, I started teaching
an introductory Finnish language

01:35:30.180 --> 01:35:33.100
community enrichment class at the
Finnish-American Heritage Center,

01:35:33.100 --> 01:35:35.240
which I continued to
teach for three years.

01:35:35.240 --> 01:35:37.940
These classes were organized into
a fall term and a winter term,

01:35:37.940 --> 01:35:40.140
consisting of a weekly
hour-long session meeting

01:35:40.140 --> 01:35:41.440
for a total of 10 weeks.

01:35:41.440 --> 01:35:43.750
So this is very low contact, right?

01:35:43.750 --> 01:35:45.470
And when I first designed
this class,

01:35:45.470 --> 01:35:47.980
I did so with very little prior
knowledge of how to go about it,

01:35:47.980 --> 01:35:49.870
and how it would work
out in reality.

01:35:49.870 --> 01:35:51.790
And so as my teaching
continued, I learned a lot

01:35:51.790 --> 01:35:54.590
about the adult motivations
for studying Finnish,

01:35:54.590 --> 01:35:56.340
and about the context and dialects

01:35:56.340 --> 01:35:58.890
in which adults were
exposed to language.

01:35:58.890 --> 01:36:01.110
The majority of my students
were locals of Finnish heritage

01:36:01.110 --> 01:36:04.340
above the age of 50, though the
classes did also attract community

01:36:04.340 --> 01:36:05.780
residents outside of the heritage.

01:36:05.780 --> 01:36:07.940
And these are two of them.

01:36:07.940 --> 01:36:10.630 position:56%
And -- Marvin and Rebecca, actually.

01:36:10.630 --> 01:36:12.490
And so these people
typically who were outside

01:36:12.490 --> 01:36:14.520
of the heritage community were
going to go visit Finland,

01:36:14.520 --> 01:36:16.510
or they were just curious about
the language, and they had --

01:36:16.510 --> 01:36:18.820
you know, just kind of a
general avocational interest.

01:36:18.820 --> 01:36:21.430
Several times, parents or
grandparents also enrolled

01:36:21.430 --> 01:36:24.010
with a child or grandchild,
and so my youngest student was

01:36:24.010 --> 01:36:26.920
about eight years old, and my
oldest students were in their 70s.

01:36:26.920 --> 01:36:30.080
One of the challenges I first
discovered in this class was

01:36:30.080 --> 01:36:32.950
that each term was essentially a
fresh start, which meant that I had

01:36:32.950 --> 01:36:35.650
to start each term at the very
beginning with Finnish alphabet

01:36:35.650 --> 01:36:38.360
and basic pronunciation rules,
though many people caught

01:36:38.360 --> 01:36:41.140
on very quickly, or had
previous exposure to it.

01:36:41.140 --> 01:36:43.450
And so, each term,
the entire six terms

01:36:43.450 --> 01:36:47.120 position:56%
that I taught included students who
also previously enrolled in a class.

01:36:47.120 --> 01:36:50.120
So one student took four
or five terms with me.

01:36:50.120 --> 01:36:51.790
And -- you know, this
-- I was like, oh, gosh,

01:36:51.790 --> 01:36:53.610
I better teach him some
other words, right?

01:36:53.610 --> 01:36:56.140
So several others came close
to this attendance record, too.

01:36:56.140 --> 01:36:58.390
And because of this, I
designed my classes to start

01:36:58.390 --> 01:37:00.780
with the basic pronunciation
and greetings, introductions,

01:37:00.780 --> 01:37:03.840
that kind of vocabulary, and then I
rotated the rest of the lesson sets

01:37:03.840 --> 01:37:05.140
around so that students enrolling

01:37:05.140 --> 01:37:08.000
in multiple years would get a
wider variety of vocabulary sets.

01:37:08.000 --> 01:37:11.540
So I would include things like
travel, work, food, home life,

01:37:11.540 --> 01:37:14.580
family and friends, animals,
all kinds of stuff like that.

01:37:14.580 --> 01:37:16.290
But that way, you wouldn't
just be getting the same thing

01:37:16.290 --> 01:37:17.680
from me every time.

01:37:17.680 --> 01:37:20.520
Several times, my academic training
in Finnish language came at odds

01:37:20.520 --> 01:37:22.820
with the daily language that
my students heard in the home.

01:37:22.820 --> 01:37:24.120
Our food unit, for instance,

01:37:24.120 --> 01:37:26.230
often had people mention
other words they knew instead,

01:37:26.230 --> 01:37:28.250
making them wonder if
they knew the wrong word.

01:37:28.250 --> 01:37:29.670
The word "fork," for
instance, [foreign language],

01:37:29.670 --> 01:37:33.140
caused one student,
very crestfallen to ask,

01:37:33.140 --> 01:37:34.440
"So you mean it's not
[foreign language]?

01:37:34.440 --> 01:37:37.100
That's the word we used at home."

01:37:37.100 --> 01:37:39.000
This example made me
incredibly excited,

01:37:39.000 --> 01:37:41.370
because it revealed another
dimension of Finnish language use

01:37:41.370 --> 01:37:44.970
in the community, in which
Swedish words were Finnicized.

01:37:44.970 --> 01:37:46.740
The word she had used
for the fork came

01:37:46.740 --> 01:37:48.040 position:56%
from the Swedish [foreign language].

01:37:48.040 --> 01:37:50.580
No, you're not wrong at all.

01:37:50.580 --> 01:37:52.140
Your family must've
come from a region

01:37:52.140 --> 01:37:53.770
that had contact with Swedish.

01:37:53.770 --> 01:37:55.870
That word is likely from
the Meankieli dialect,

01:37:55.870 --> 01:37:57.170
which is really interesting.

01:37:57.170 --> 01:37:59.170
And that's a really
beautiful dialect of Finnish.

01:37:59.170 --> 01:38:00.670
Like, that's exciting.

01:38:00.670 --> 01:38:03.170
So, you know, I got exposure to
these kind of things all the time.

01:38:03.170 --> 01:38:07.660
The word potato also
caused a lot of problems.

01:38:07.660 --> 01:38:08.960
[Laughter] They -- I always
say [foreign language],

01:38:08.960 --> 01:38:10.260
and they always say
[foreign language].

01:38:10.260 --> 01:38:12.600
So, as I continued my
teaching, it became clear early

01:38:12.600 --> 01:38:16.120
on that fluency was not the object
for the vast majority of students.

01:38:16.120 --> 01:38:18.440
They realized they were beyond the
peak language acquisition years

01:38:18.440 --> 01:38:19.740
of youth.

01:38:19.740 --> 01:38:23.130
So for them, instead, the emotional
component was much more important.

01:38:23.130 --> 01:38:25.200
They wanted to understand
the words to hymns

01:38:25.200 --> 01:38:27.100
and nursery rhymes
that they remembered.

01:38:27.100 --> 01:38:28.870
They wanted to talk about
food they still ate,

01:38:28.870 --> 01:38:31.350
and about cousins they
had visited in Finland.

01:38:31.350 --> 01:38:33.980
The language class was a window
to a whole world of Finnishness

01:38:33.980 --> 01:38:36.340
in which they were
active participants.

01:38:36.340 --> 01:38:38.920
Our class was a farm for nostalgia,
and for making connections

01:38:38.920 --> 01:38:42.110
between the Finnish-American
experience and Finnishness itself.

01:38:42.110 --> 01:38:45.510 position:56%
Sometimes, the simple act of rolling
our ehrs [phonetic] and saying ah,

01:38:45.510 --> 01:38:47.890
ih, ew [phonetic] in rapid
succession was what was

01:38:47.890 --> 01:38:49.190
most important.

01:38:49.190 --> 01:38:51.640
Sometimes reflecting on the
Finland of today and the Finland

01:38:51.640 --> 01:38:55.550
that their ancestors knew
was what was most important.

01:38:55.550 --> 01:38:59.360
So one fall afternoon, in 2012,
I walked into Karvakko's Market

01:38:59.360 --> 01:39:02.820
in Tapiola, Michigan with the
rather unusual task of picking

01:39:02.820 --> 01:39:05.930
up deer tongues that had been
promised to my husband for use

01:39:05.930 --> 01:39:09.460
in a pate he planned to make
in a Finnish cooking workshop.

01:39:09.460 --> 01:39:12.130
So I married a man who's not
Finnish at all, but he has come

01:39:12.130 --> 01:39:13.610
to be a wonderful Finnish cook.

01:39:13.610 --> 01:39:16.410
So if you ever need one, and
you're in Hancock, give me a call.

01:39:16.410 --> 01:39:19.580
A man maybe about 15 years
older than I entered,

01:39:19.580 --> 01:39:21.360
and began a conversation
with the store proprietor,

01:39:21.360 --> 01:39:22.660
who appeared to be in his 60s.

01:39:22.660 --> 01:39:24.720
And they spoke completely
in Finnish.

01:39:24.720 --> 01:39:27.560 position:56%
So I grabbed a few other items and
waited for their conversation to end

01:39:27.560 --> 01:39:28.860
so I could ask for
these deer tongues.

01:39:28.860 --> 01:39:31.760
And periodically, the men would
cast mischievous glances my way,

01:39:31.760 --> 01:39:35.040
and I could tell that they really
enjoyed their talking in front

01:39:35.040 --> 01:39:38.130
of an unfamiliar woman in what they
assumed to be a secret language.

01:39:38.130 --> 01:39:40.250
Their conversation was
mundane, and not offensive,

01:39:40.250 --> 01:39:42.780
and so I let them have their
fun until another glance

01:39:42.780 --> 01:39:48.550
with a big grin came my way, and
I decided to call their game.

01:39:48.550 --> 01:39:49.850
[Foreign language].

01:39:49.850 --> 01:39:51.150
So, we speak Finnish here, then?

01:39:51.150 --> 01:39:53.700
Their smiles erupted into laughter,
and they switched into English.

01:39:53.700 --> 01:39:55.830
I admitted that my grandfather
was from just up the road,

01:39:55.830 --> 01:39:57.670
and they promptly gave
me hugs and handshakes,

01:39:57.670 --> 01:39:59.600
and shared memories
of Frannie Virtanen.

01:39:59.600 --> 01:40:02.060
Finnish lives in pockets.

01:40:02.060 --> 01:40:04.580 position:56%
Often at about 10 a.m. on
weekdays, you can find a small group

01:40:04.580 --> 01:40:06.990
of elders speaking together
in Finnish over coffee

01:40:06.990 --> 01:40:08.840
at a local bakery in Houghton.

01:40:08.840 --> 01:40:11.520
You can find Finnish hymns sung
at Laestadian religious services,

01:40:11.520 --> 01:40:14.170
and at funerals for members
of the Ladies of Kaleva,

01:40:14.170 --> 01:40:16.170
which is a Finnish-American
fraternal order.

01:40:16.170 --> 01:40:18.280
It is used symbolically
on bumper stickers.

01:40:18.280 --> 01:40:22.060 position:56%
It is a resource for those needing
particularly satisfying swear words,

01:40:22.060 --> 01:40:23.360
and it is a greeting to use

01:40:23.360 --> 01:40:25.810
